      "risk_profile": {},
      "business_constraints": {
        "assistant_drafted_requirements_count": 7,
        "assistant_drafted_requirements_summary": "Expose Jira through governed business capabilities rather than raw tools: The product shall present Jira as a bounded ANIP capability surface for agents and browser users. It shall not expose raw Jira REST endpoints, raw MCP tools, or unrestricted low-level operations directly. Capability entry points shall use business-oriented intents such as issue context, backlog context, and governed change requests.\nAllow only bounded read-only Jira context: The product shall support read-only access to Jira issue context and backlog context within allowed Jira scope. Returned data shall be limited to actor-visible, bounded business context rather than unbounded exports or arbitrary query access. The system shall prevent raw JQL exposure and other mechanisms that could bypass bounded retrieval.\nGate all write-adjacent Jira actions at preview or approval: For write-adjacent Jira actions, the product shall stop before direct mutation unless an explicit approval path is satisfied. This applies to comments, subtasks, stories, incident bugs, assignee changes, sprint moves, workflow transitions, issue links, and release notes. The system shall return a preview or approval-ready request rather than silently executing the Jira change.\nRequire clarification when required inputs are missing: When a requested Jira capability lacks required inputs, policy context, or target scope, the product shall ask for clarification instead of guessing defaults or inferring unsafe values. Clarification prompts should identify the missing business input needed to continue the governed flow.\nEnforce actor-visible scope and approval policy on every governed action: The product shall evaluate each read and write-adjacent request against actor-visible Jira scope and applicable approval policy before returning results or advancing a request. Where policy requires approval, the system shall stop at the approval boundary and present the request in a reviewable form. Where scope or policy denies access, the system shall not reveal out-of-scope Jira data.\nRecord audit evidence for previews, approvals, and governed stops: The product shall record audit evidence for write-adjacent previews, approval-required requests, and policy-driven stop conditions. Audit evidence should capture enough context to show what was requested, what Jira scope and policy were applied, what preview was produced, and why execution did or did not proceed.\nSupport clean browser UI verification of governed Jira fronting: The first release shall support browser-verifiable flows that demonstrate the governed fronting behavior end to end. Verification should show that users can access bounded Jira context, receive previews for write-adjacent actions, encounter approval stops where required, and observe that raw Jira tools are not exposed through the UI."
      }
    }
  },
